body:
Most of this PR was already reviewed. See the last commit for the latest changes needed to get this to pass 1000s of dunitrunner and cross-section testing runs.

The actual fix for the last source of flakiness was to use Awaitility in client2 near the end of testBug51725:
```
    client2.invoke(() -> {
      await().untilAsserted(() -> {
        Region<String, TickerData> region = getCache().getRegion(regionName);
        for (int i = 0; i < ONE_HUNDRED; i++) {
          Entry<String, TickerData> regionEntry = region.getEntry(title + i);
          assertThat(regionEntry).isNull();
        }
      });
    });
```
The other sources of flakiness were fixed in the 2nd commit which overhauled the entire test to use CountDownLatches instead of the broken Object/wait/notify pattern. Another earlier source of flakiness was the use of an immutable boolean condition instead of a lambda/runnable/mutable-condition for a wait condition.

On this branch, PutAllClientServerDistributedTest passes 1000 dunitrunner runs as well as cross-section 16 1000.

The Pdx configuration class no longer has the persistent attribute and now has a new AutoSerializer attribute.
The persistent attribute was not needed because it is implied by having a non-null diskStoreName.
The autoSerializer attribute allow the ReflectionBasedAutoSerializer to be used more easily.
Before it would look something like this in json: pdxSerializer:{className:"org.apache.geode.pdx.ReflectionBasedAutoSerializer", initProperties:{"classes", "pat1,pat2"}}
Now in json: autoSerializer: {patterns:["pat1", "pat2"]}
